      "skillMarkdown": "# Clear Browsing Data and Site Data\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\nUse this skill when the task asks Chrome or Chromium to do any of the following:\n\n- clear browsing history, cached images/files, cookies, or other browsing-data categories\n- open the Delete browsing data workflow and choose a time range or tab before deleting\n- remove stored data for a specific site from the All sites page\n- verify that browsing data or site-specific stored data is no longer present\n\nDo not use this skill for unrelated settings such as performance, appearance, startup, extensions, or permissions unless the task also explicitly includes browsing-data or site-data cleanup.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Chrome or Chromium is open and can reach Settings.\n- The task text identifies what should be removed: bulk browsing data, certain categories, or data for a named site.\n- If the runtime UI differs from the screenshots, follow the semantic Chrome labels rather than screen coordinates.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- detailed cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- Compact runtime cards live in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Runtime should load only the card or cards whose `when_to_use` match the current screenshot and subgoal. Do not preload every image card.\n\nUse the matching image card only when the current UI actually resembles that state:\n\n- `Images/delete_browsing_data_dialog.png`: the three-dot menu path is open and Delete browsing data is visible in the submenu.\n- `Images/advanced_tab_and_time_range.png`: the Delete browsing data modal is open and the task still needs a tab or time-range decision.\n- `Images/delete_data_button.png`: the dialog selections are already set and the next action is the Delete data commit button.\n- `Images/site_data_target_row.png`: the All sites page is open and the task concerns row-level site-data inspection, deletion, or verification.\n\nRed boxes are interaction cues. Green boxes are state or verification cues. Neither color provides reusable coordinates.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Read the task carefully and determine whether it wants bulk browsing-data cleanup or data removal for one named site.\n2. For bulk cleanup, open Chrome's Delete browsing data workflow from the three-dot menu, Settings search, or direct settings navigation.\n3. Inside the dialog, choose the required tab, time range, and data categories. If the task says to clear all browsing data, use the broadest applicable time range and include the requested categories.\n4. Trigger `Delete data` only after the dialog selections match the task.\n5. For site-specific cleanup, open `Settings > Privacy and security > Site settings > All sites`, locate the target site, and remove its stored data using the control that matches the current UI.\n6. Verify the result from the post-action state instead of assuming success from the click alone.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy example time ranges, checkbox states, domain names, cookie counts, storage totals, menu order, theme, or scroll position from the screenshots.\n- Treat boxed regions as recognition hints only. They are not reusable coordinates and should not be turned into fixed clicks.\n- The screenshot filenames are not always literal descriptions of what is visible; rely on the card text and current UI state.\n- Ignore source-task-only follow-on actions that are unrelated to browsing-data or site-data cleanup.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- Bulk deletion is only credible after the Delete browsing data dialog closes or Chrome returns to a stable settings surface without another required confirmation.\n- For site-specific cleanup, verify the target site named in the current task, not the example domains in the image cards.\n- A remaining site row on the All sites page usually means stored data still exists for that site.\n- If needed, search or refresh the All sites page to confirm that the target row is gone or no longer shows relevant stored data.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Opening the deletion workflow correctly but deleting with the wrong time range or wrong category selection.\n- Treating the menu item or Delete data button state as completion evidence.\n- Clearing all browsing data when the task only asked for one site's stored data.\n- Reusing example domains or storage values from the screenshots instead of the current task's target.\n- Marking success while the target site row, deletion modal, or another blocking confirmation is still present.",
