      "skillMarkdown": "# Enable Live Caption and Webpage Translation\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\nUse this skill when a Chrome task asks you to change browser-level translation or caption settings in Chrome Settings. Typical cases:\n\n- enable webpage translation or set the language Chrome should translate pages into;\n- enable `Live Caption`;\n- enable `Live Translate` and choose the caption translation target language;\n- verify that Chrome Settings visibly reflects the requested caption or translation result.\n\nDo not use this skill for a page-level translate bubble alone unless the task explicitly requires Settings changes.\n\n## Text-First Procedure\n\n1. Open the needed Chrome settings surface directly when possible:\n   - webpage translation: `chrome://settings/languages`\n   - caption settings: `chrome://settings/accessibility` and then `Captions`, or `chrome://settings/captions`\n2. On the Languages page, locate the `Google Translate` section. Enable webpage translation if requested, then set `Translate into this language` to the requested language.\n3. If you are on the Accessibility overview, open the `Captions` row.\n4. On the Captions page, enable `Live Caption` if the task asks for captions or live subtitles.\n5. If the required caption language is unavailable, use `Add languages`, select the requested language in the modal, and confirm it.\n6. Enable `Live Translate` if requested, then set `Translate captions to` to the requested target language.\n7. Verify the final state before stopping:\n   - webpage translation is enabled and points to the requested language when required;\n   - `Live Caption` is enabled when required;\n   - `Live Translate` is enabled and `Translate captions to` shows the requested language when required.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nThis package has two visual-card files:\n\n- `state_cards.json`: full detailed version with evidence notes and transfer limits\n- `runtime_state_cards.json`: compact version for runtime branch loading\n\nLoad only the card whose `when_to_use` matches the current screenshot. Do not load all image cards by default. If the runtime already knows the current surface, match only the corresponding card from `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n\nCurrent image references:\n\n- `Images/captions_settings_surface.png`: Languages page with the `Google Translate` section visible\n- `Images/live_caption_toggle.png`: Accessibility overview with the `Captions` row marked as the next interaction cue\n- `Images/live_translate_language_state.png`: `Add languages` modal on the Captions page\n- `Images/translation_features_enabled.png`: Captions page with the `Translate captions to` field serving as the final verification cue\n\nRed boxes are interaction cues after the UI state is matched. Green boxes are state or result cues. Neither color provides reusable coordinates.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\nTreat each image as an example state, not a template to copy literally. Transfer only the visible UI relationship between the settings surface and the marked control or verification cue.\n\nDo not transfer:\n\n- exact click coordinates, box sizes, scroll offsets, or browser window geometry;\n- example language values unless the current task requests the same language;\n- unrelated toggle states, caption appearance settings, preferred-language lists, or never-translate lists;\n- modal search text or dropdown contents that came from the source example.\n\nIf Chrome's layout differs but the same setting is clearly present, follow the text-first procedure and use the matching visual card only as supporting state evidence.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\nFor webpage translation, verify the Languages page shows the `Google Translate` section with translation enabled if requested and the correct target language selected.\n\nFor caption tasks, verify the Captions page shows `Live Caption` enabled. If the task required adding a language, verify that language appears in the supported Live Caption languages list.\n\nFor caption translation, verify `Live Translate` is enabled and the `Translate captions to` selector shows the requested language. If the task also asked for webpage translation, perform a separate verification on the Languages page; the Captions-page verification is not enough by itself.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- stopping on `chrome://settings/accessibility` without opening `Captions`;\n- selecting a language in `Add languages` but not confirming it;\n- copying the example language from a screenshot instead of the language named by the current task;\n- verifying `Live Translate` on the Captions page but forgetting the separate webpage-translation verification on the Languages page.",
