      "skillMarkdown": "# Filter and Sort Google Maps Reviews\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\nUse this skill in Chrome when Google Maps is already open and the task requires any of the following:\n\n- narrowing visible results with a category or nearby business filter\n- opening a place's Reviews tab\n- changing the review ordering\n- expanding truncated review text before reading it\n\nThe task should already identify the target place, category, review order, or review count closely enough that the next action can be chosen from the current screen.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nThis is a text-first OSWorld skill. Use the procedure text to decide the next action, and use image cards only to confirm that the current screen matches the expected state.\n\n- `state_cards.json` is the full audit file with one detailed card per image.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact Agent branch file. Load only the card whose `when_to_use` best matches the live screen.\n\nCurrent image-state mapping:\n\n- `Images/category_filter_selection.png`: left sidebar category row is visible and ready to narrow results\n- `Images/reviews_tab_selection.png`: place detail sheet is open and the Reviews tab is the next target\n- `Images/sort_dropdown_newest.png`: review sort dropdown is open and a sort option should be selected\n- `Images/expand_review_content.png`: a review is truncated and a More control should be used\n\nRed boxes mark interaction cues. Green boxes mark state or verification cues. They help identify the right control or result signal and are never reusable coordinates.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy place names, neighborhoods, reviewer names, review text, dates, prices, ratings, result order, or map positions from the example images.\n- Do not assume the pictured hotel context applies to the live task.\n- Do not assume the pictured sort option is always correct; choose the order requested by the current instruction.\n- Do not assume the pictured review row is the correct one to expand; match the live review requested by the task.\n- If the UI is localized or shifted by viewport size, transfer by label meaning and surrounding layout, not by exact position.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### 1. Narrow Results When Needed\n\nIf Google Maps is still showing a search-results sidebar and the task requires a business type, use the matching category row from the current page. The image reference for this state is `Images/category_filter_selection.png`.\n\nVerify that the visible results list or map updates toward the requested category before moving on.\n\n### 2. Open the Reviews Tab\n\nWhen a specific place detail sheet is open, find the tab strip and open Reviews if it is not already active. The matching visual reference is `Images/reviews_tab_selection.png`.\n\nContinue only after review-specific UI appears, such as rating bars, review counts, review filters, a search field, a sort control, or review cards.\n\n### 3. Apply the Requested Review Order\n\nIf the task specifies newest, highest rating, lowest rating, most relevant, or another visible review order, open the sort dropdown and choose the matching option. The image reference for the open-menu state is `Images/sort_dropdown_newest.png`.\n\nDo not inherit the example option by default. Verify the applied order from the visible selection label or the ordering of the top review entries.\n\n### 4. Expand Truncated Review Text\n\nWhen a target review is cut off, click the More control on that review card and read the expanded text. The image reference for this state is `Images/expand_review_content.png`.\n\nRepeat for each requested review if the task asks for more than one.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The active surface is the Reviews section when the task is about review inspection.\n- A category filter, if used, has visibly changed the results toward the requested business type.\n- The selected review ordering matches the instruction and is reflected by visible labels, timestamps, ratings, or row order.\n- Any review that needed expansion is fully readable after the More action.\n- The final extracted information comes from the live page, not from example screenshots.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Selecting the example hotel category when the task actually names another business type.\n- Clicking the Reviews tab area after reviews are already active and misreading the lack of change as failure.\n- Opening the sort menu but never choosing the requested ordering.\n- Treating the example Newest option as mandatory for every task.\n- Expanding the wrong review row or assuming one More action reveals every needed review.",
