      "skillMarkdown": "# Manage Preferred Languages And Interface Language\n\nUse this skill for Chrome language-management tasks on the Settings > Languages surface: opening the Languages page, adding a preferred language, reordering or removing language rows, adjusting row-level behavior, and checking translate buckets or interface-language controls when those controls are present.\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\n- The task is about Chrome preferred languages, translate-language lists, spell-check language lists, or the Chrome interface language when that option is exposed.\n- Chrome Settings can be opened and the Languages page is reachable from the left sidebar.\n- Success depends on a persistent language state, such as a new row appearing, a row moving, or a translate bucket changing.\n\nDo not use this skill for webpage translation popups on normal sites, account profile language settings, or operating-system language settings outside Chrome.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact runtime set for the Agent branch. Load only the card or cards whose `when_to_use` and visible cues match the current screenshot.\n- `state_cards.json` is the detailed version with fuller reasoning, transfer limits, and review rationale.\n- Red boxes are action cues that show which UI element mattered in the example.\n- Green boxes are state or verification cues that show what confirmed progress in the example.\n- Boxes are never reusable coordinates. Match by UI structure and labels, not by pixel position.\n\nCurrent image references:\n\n- `Images/languages_settings_surface.png`\n- `Images/add_language_dialog.png`\n- `Images/language_behavior_menu.png`\n- `Images/language_list_updated.png`\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Reach the Languages page in Chrome Settings.\n   If Chrome is already in Settings but not on Languages, use the sidebar navigation and confirm the main panel switches to the Languages surface. `Images/languages_settings_surface.png` is the entry cue for this transition.\n\n2. Add a language when the task requires a new preferred language or a new language in a translate-related list.\n   From the Preferred languages card or the relevant translate bucket, open the add flow, search for the requested language, select the matching row, then commit the dialog. `Images/add_language_dialog.png` is the page-level cue for opening the picker. `Images/language_list_updated.png` is a dialog-level cue for confirming that the requested row has been found and checked before you press Add.\n\n3. Use the row-level overflow control when the language already exists in the list.\n   Open the three-dot menu on the relevant row to move the language, remove it, or expose display-language behavior when Chrome offers that option. `Images/language_behavior_menu.png` is the cue for that row-level action state.\n\n4. Verify the persistent result on the main page before finishing.\n   The task is only complete when the main Languages surface reflects the requested change after any dialog closes: the language row is present, absent, or reordered as requested; the translate buckets contain the requested languages; or the interface-language choice is visibly updated when supported by the current Chrome build.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy example language names from the screenshots unless the current task explicitly asks for them.\n- Do not assume the same existing list order, translate toggle state, or Chrome build-specific controls will be present.\n- Do not reuse the boxed positions, crop boundaries, or row coordinates.\n- Treat the screenshots as state-recognition aids only. The runtime should adapt to the live UI labels and available controls.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The Languages page is still open after the action, and the relevant section shows the requested state.\n- A preferred language row appears in the expected position or is removed from the list.\n- The correct translate bucket shows the requested language added or removed.\n- If an interface-language control is relevant and available, the selected language or relaunch-required state is visibly tied to the requested language.\n- A dialog-level confirmation, such as a checked row in the Add languages picker, is intermediate evidence only; final completion still requires a persistent page-level result when the task asks for it.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Stopping after opening the dialog without committing the selected language.\n- Verifying only the checked row inside the picker and not the persistent list after the dialog closes.\n- Opening the overflow menu on the wrong language row because several similar rows are present.\n- Confusing Chrome Settings language management with translation prompts shown on ordinary webpages.\n- Assuming interface-language controls exist on every build; use them only when visible in the live UI.",
