      "skillMarkdown": "# Manage Profile Theme Avatar And Home Button\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\nUse this skill when the task is to change one of these Chrome profile-level settings:\n\n- profile name\n- profile avatar\n- profile theme color\n- home-button visibility or its paired home-page behavior\n\nThis skill is appropriate when Chrome Settings is available and you can reach either the profile customization surface or the Appearance page.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- Audit-ready image cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- The compact runtime set for the Agent branch lives in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Load only the card or cards whose screenshot genuinely matches the current screen. Do not load the whole image set by default.\n- Treat red boxes as interaction cues and green boxes as state or verification cues. They are not reusable coordinates.\n- Keep the procedure text as the primary guide. The images are supporting state-recognition aids, not a substitute for navigation.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy example values from the screenshots. The shown profile name, selected pink theme, example avatar, notification exception, and saved address details are source-specific.\n- `Images/show_home_button_toggle.png` is lineage-preserved but does not actually show the Appearance home-button toggle. Use it only as weak supplemental evidence that a profile theme can persist on another Settings page.\n- `Images/profile_or_home_state_visible.png` is a good profile-theme verification image, but it is not a direct home-button verification image.\n- When the runtime branch is on a nonmatching Settings subpage, ignore the image cards and continue with the text procedure until the screen matches again.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Open the correct Chrome settings surface.\n   - For profile name, theme, or avatar changes, reach the profile customization page where the name field, theme swatches, and avatar grid are visible.\n   - For home-button changes, reach the Appearance settings section where the home-button toggle is available.\n2. Make the requested change.\n   - Edit the profile name only if the task asks for a name change.\n   - Pick the requested theme swatch or avatar icon when working on profile customization.\n   - Enable or disable the home button as requested, and adjust any related home-page option only if the task explicitly asks for it.\n3. Verify the persistent result before stopping.\n   - A theme change should remain visible in the browser frame or tab strip.\n   - A profile avatar or name change should be visible on the relevant profile surface or profile entry point.\n   - A home-button change should be confirmed on the Appearance page and, when visible in the toolbar layout, by the home icon being present or absent as requested.\n\n## Image References\n\n- `Images/customize_profile_surface.png`: strong entry-state cue for the profile customization surface.\n- `Images/profile_theme_or_avatar_choice.png`: strong operation-state cue for choosing a theme or avatar.\n- `Images/show_home_button_toggle.png`: supplemental evidence only; do not use it as direct home-button proof.\n- `Images/profile_or_home_state_visible.png`: strong verification cue for persistent profile-theme changes.\n\nThe runtime should load only the matching image cards, not every image listed above.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The requested theme tint appears in the browser frame and remains visible after moving to another Chrome page.\n- The requested avatar shows as the selected profile image.\n- The requested profile name is present in the profile customization field or another profile-visible surface.\n- The home button is enabled or disabled as requested on the Appearance page, and the toolbar state matches when that cue is visible.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Acting on a Settings page that looks similar but is not the correct surface for the requested change.\n- Copying the example pink theme or example avatar when the task asks for a different choice.\n- Treating the notification or address screenshots as part of the home-button procedure.\n- Ending after a click without checking for a persistent visual result.",
