      "skillMarkdown": "# Navigate to Google Services via Apps Menu\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\nUse this skill when the task is to open a Google service such as Drive, Photos, Maps, YouTube, Gmail, or a similar Google app from the Google Apps launcher in Chrome.\n\nThis skill fits when:\n\n- Chrome is already open on a surface where the Google Apps launcher is available.\n- The task needs navigation through the 3x3 Google Apps grid rather than direct URL entry.\n- Completion depends on the requested Google service page becoming visibly open.\n\nDo not use this skill when the launcher is unavailable on the current page, when the task is about Chrome settings rather than Google services, or when the destination service is already open.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- The current Chrome surface exposes the Google Apps launcher.\n- The user can access the requested Google service from that launcher.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nThis skill remains text-first. Use the procedure below as the main instruction path.\n\nImage cards are supporting cues:\n\n- Audit file: `state_cards.json`\n- Runtime file for the Agent branch: `runtime_state_cards.json`\n\nLoad only the card whose `when_to_use` matches the current screen. Do not load every image card by default. If the current screen no longer matches a card, switch back to the text procedure or the next matching card.\n\nRed boxes are interaction cues. Green boxes are state or verification cues. They show what to look at, not where to click by coordinate.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Treat each image as one example of a reusable UI state, not as a literal template.\n- Do not transfer exact tile positions, page text, account-specific content, or browser-theme details from the screenshots.\n- The service shown in a verification image may be an example only. The runtime should verify the service requested by the current task.\n- Use image references already embedded in the procedure only when the current screen plausibly matches that state.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### 1. Identify the Google Apps launcher\n\nLook at the top-right area of the Chrome toolbar for the 3x3 Google Apps grid icon.\n\nImage reference if needed: `Images/browser_toolbar_apps_icon.png`\n\n### 2. Open the Apps menu and choose the requested service\n\nActivate the launcher, then confirm that an apps panel opens with Google service tiles. Find the tile for the requested service and select it.\n\nImage reference if needed: `Images/google_apps_menu_grid.png`\n\nIf the requested tile is not immediately visible, scan within the panel before assuming the skill does not apply.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\nThe skill is complete only when the browser shows the requested Google service as a loaded page.\n\nVerify:\n\n- the apps menu is no longer the active surface\n- the main page now shows the destination Google service interface\n- the address bar/domain matches the requested service\n\nImage reference if needed: `Images/google_drive_loaded.png`\n\nUse the runtime card for that image only when the current page is already in a post-navigation state.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- The current page does not expose the Google Apps launcher.\n- The apps panel opens, but the requested service tile is not visible without scrolling.\n- Selecting the tile opens a sign-in or access gate instead of the service home page.\n- The loaded page is a Google service, but not the one requested by the task.",
