      "skillMarkdown": "# Search And Sort Flight Results\n\n## Overview\n\nUse Google Flights search and results surfaces to set route, trip type, passenger count, dates, and sorting on Google Flights. Keep this skill as the default for plain Google Flights tasks, and switch to the broader travel-booking skill only after a hotel, car-rental, or non-Google booking surface is clearly open.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Searching flights in Google Flights\n- Setting one-way or round-trip parameters, passenger count, and dates\n- Opening or verifying the Google Flights results list\n- Applying a Google Flights sort or confirming that the visible list already matches the requested constraint\n\n## Do Not Use\n\n- Hotel, vacation-rental, or car-rental result pages\n- Airline or travel-vendor booking pages that already left Google Flights\n- Generic site navigation tasks that only need a target page URL\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- The origin, destination, and date requirements are already known from the task.\n- Chrome is either on Google Travel, Google Flights, or a page that can immediately move into Google Flights.\n\n## Visual Annotation Conventions\n\n- Red boxes mark action targets.\n- Green boxes mark verification or recovery signals.\n\n## Procedures\n\n### 1. Reach The Google Flights Working Surface\n\n- If Chrome is still on the broader Google Travel landing page, move into the Flights tab first.\n- If the Google Flights form is already open, stay on that surface instead of detouring through search or unrelated travel flows.\n- If the results list is already open with the correct route, keep the agent on that live results page and continue from there.\n- Image: `Images/google_flights_search_surface.png`\n\n### 2. Set Route, Trip Type, Travelers, And Dates\n\n- Use the Google Flights form controls to set or correct the route, trip type, traveler count, and dates requested by the task.\n- Re-check the visible form values before submitting; do not assume an earlier value persisted after editing another field.\n- If the task only asks for a route lookup and the form already shows the correct values, avoid reopening fields unnecessarily.\n- Images:\n  - `Images/one_way_trip_type_selected.png`\n  - `Images/departure_date_picker.png`\n\n### 3. Run The Search And Stay On Google Flights Results\n\n- Submit the query only after the visible route and date controls match the task.\n- Once Google Flights results are open, keep working on that results page rather than jumping to airline checkout pages unless the task explicitly requires that.\n- Apply a Google Flights sort only when the task asks for it, or verify the current results if the requested state is already visible.\n- Image: `Images/flight_results_sorted_state.png`\n\n### 4. Verify Before Ending\n\n- Confirm the page is still Google Flights, not a generic travel homepage or an airline vendor page.\n- Confirm the route, date, and any requested sort/filter state are visible on the live results surface.\n- For flight-only tasks, end on the stable results list rather than on an intermediate popup, date picker, or route form.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Editing Google Flights fields but never reaching a stable results list.\n- Leaving a valid Google Flights results page to chase an external airline page that the verification does not require.\n- Mixing this skill with hotel or car-rental filter patterns that belong to the broader travel-booking skill.\n- Reopening date or trip-type controls after the correct values are already visible, which often resets a nearly-complete query.\n\n## Runtime Assets\n\n- `state_cards.json` carries the richer multiview authoring bundle.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` carries the slimmer runtime-facing card set.",
