      "skillMarkdown": "# Select Transportation Mode\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\nUse this skill when Google Maps directions are already open in Chrome and the task is to change the route mode, such as driving, transit, walking, or cycling.\n\nUse it when:\n- the origin and destination are already entered\n- the current route mode does not match the requested one\n- completion depends on proving that the new mode is selected\n\nDo not use it for general map search, opening directions from scratch, or validating route content that is unrelated to the mode switch itself.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nThis is a text-first skill. Follow the procedure from text, and use image cards only when the current screenshot plausibly matches the same UI state.\n\n- `state_cards.json` is the full detailed version with detailed transfer limits and evidence lineage.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact version intended for runtime branch loading.\n- Load only the card or cards whose `when_to_use` conditions match the current screenshot.\n- Treat red boxes as interaction cues and green boxes as state or verification cues.\n- Never reuse box coordinates as click positions.\n\nImage references used by this skill:\n- `Images/directions_panel_with_mode_icons.png`\n- `Images/clicking_transit_icon.png`\n- `Images/walking_route_displayed.png`\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy the example route names, cities, times, distances, or route ordering from the screenshots.\n- Do not rely on the exact browser window size, theme, bookmarks bar, language, or map region.\n- Transfer the UI relationship only: directions panel present, mode row present, requested icon clicked, requested mode becomes active, route results refresh.\n- If Google Maps presents the same controls in a slightly different layout, follow the control meaning rather than the example spacing.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Confirm that Google Maps is already on a directions page with origin and destination fields populated.\n2. Locate the transportation mode row near the top of the directions panel. Look for icons such as driving, transit, walking, and cycling.\n3. Identify the icon that matches the requested transportation mode.\n4. Click that mode icon once.\n5. Wait for the panel and map to refresh.\n6. Verify that the requested mode icon is now visually active and that the route list or map path has updated to match that mode.\n\nIf the requested icon is missing, disabled, or no route is available for that mode, stop treating this as a successful mode switch and reassess the page state.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\nUse the mode switch as complete only when both cues are present:\n\n- the requested transportation icon is visibly active in the mode row\n- the route results below, the route path on the map, or both have refreshed to the selected mode\n\n`Images/walking_route_displayed.png` is an example verification frame. The reusable pattern is not the literal walking route values; it is the combination of an active mode icon and updated route results.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Clicking the wrong icon because similar symbols were scanned too quickly.\n- Acting before the directions panel fully loads, so the click does not change the route.\n- Mistaking the presence of the mode row for successful completion.\n- Treating example route details from the screenshot as required verification values.\n- Attempting to verify success before Google Maps finishes recalculating the route.\n\n## Artifacts\n\n- Audit detail: `state_cards.json`\n- Runtime card set: `runtime_state_cards.json`\n- Planning source: `plan.json`",
