      "skillMarkdown": "# Sort News Results by Time\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\nUse this skill when Chrome is already showing a news or site-search results list and the task asks you to:\n\n- change the list to newest, latest, or another time-based order\n- verify that the list is actually sorted by time rather than relevance\n- open a requested result after the sort is applied, such as the first, second, or another ranked article\n\nDo not use this skill for general web searching from scratch, for pages that do not expose any sort control, or after you have already reached the final article page and no sorting step remains.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- A news or site-search results list is already visible.\n- The page exposes a sort control such as `Newest`, `Latest`, or `Relevancy`.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Confirm that you are still on a results page, not inside a single article.\n   - Look for a results count or multiple article cards in one list.\n   - Look for a sort-control cluster near the top of the results list.\n   - Matching image card: `Images/search_results_unsorted_or_default.png`\n\n2. Locate the time-sort control and activate it.\n   - Click the control labeled `Newest`, `Latest`, or the closest equivalent.\n   - Use the matching card for the control location only; the box is not a coordinate recipe.\n   - Matching image card: `Images/click_newest_sort_button.png`\n\n3. Verify that the sort actually changed.\n   - Success means the time-sort option is visibly selected and the result list reflects recency.\n   - If the live page still resembles a relevance-sorted list, the sort did not apply yet.\n   - Counterexample image card: `Images/newest_sort_confirmed.png`\n\n4. Open the requested result from the newly sorted list.\n   - If the task specifies a rank such as second article, count within the current sorted list, not the old order.\n   - Click the main result headline in the list, not a sidebar recommendation or related-story tile.\n\n5. Verify that the article page loaded.\n   - Confirm the browser has navigated away from the results page into a specific article page.\n   - Use the article headline plus nearby metadata such as the byline or timestamp.\n   - Matching image card: `Images/select_second_article.png`\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- Audit-rich image cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- The compact runtime cards that the Agent branch should load live in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Load only the cards whose `when_to_use` matches the current screenshot. Ignore cards whose `when_not_to_use` matches, even if the filename sounds related.\n- The runtime should not preload every image blindly. It should select only the cards relevant to the current page surface or verification step.\n- Red boxes are interaction cues. Green boxes are state or verification cues. Neither is a reusable coordinate.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy the example query terms, result counts, article topics, dates, headlines, author names, or URL fragments into a new task unless the live task explicitly requires them.\n- Do not assume the exact site layout, pill styling, or result-card spacing will match the screenshots.\n- Some filenames reflect the source capture rather than the idealized state. Trust the card text and the live UI, not the filename alone.\n- Treat any boxed sidebar item or unrelated recommendation as non-transferable unless the live task explicitly asks you to open it.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- On the results page, the time-based sort option should be visibly selected instead of `Relevancy` or another default order.\n- The results should still appear as a list of articles after the sort refreshes.\n- When the requested result is opened, the page should become an article-detail page with a prominent headline and nearby metadata.\n- Use more than one cue when possible: page type, selected sort control, article headline, and timestamp together are stronger than any single cue alone.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Clicking a sort pill but continuing immediately before the page refresh completes.\n- Mistaking a relevance-selected page for a successful newest sort.\n- Counting article rank from the pre-sort order instead of the refreshed list.\n- Clicking a related-story tile or sidebar recommendation after the article page loads.\n- Treating a red or green box as a pixel coordinate instead of a visual cue.\n\n## Files\n\n- `plan.json` is the text procedure source for this skill.\n- `state_cards.json` is the detailed audit file for the image cards.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact file intended for runtime branch loading.",
