      "skillMarkdown": "# Travel Results And Booking Filters\n\n## Overview\n\nUse travel-booking result surfaces to filter or sort hotel, car-rental, and vendor booking pages, adjust travel constraints that are already on those surfaces, and recover from browser-level booking failures. Do not use this as the first-choice skill for plain Google Flights tasks.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Sorting or filtering hotel, car-rental, or non-Google vendor booking result pages\n- Changing dates, traveler settings, or price/capacity constraints on those result pages\n- Recovering from unresponsive travel booking pages before retrying the same task\n\n## Do Not Use\n\n- Plain Google Flights form tasks that stay inside Google Flights\n- Generic web navigation tasks that only need a destination page URL\n- Shopping or ecommerce product pages that only happen to mention travel-related words\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Chrome is already on a travel planner, result page, or booking page with travel-specific controls.\n- The requested route, city, date range, or traveler constraint is already known from the task.\n\n## Visual Annotation Conventions\n\n- Red boxes mark action targets.\n- Green boxes mark verification or recovery signals.\n\n## Procedures\n\n### 1. Confirm You Are On A Travel-Booking Surface\n\n- Use this skill only after a page already shows travel-specific controls such as route, date, traveler, price, seat-capacity, or booking filters.\n- If the page is clearly the Google Flights planner and the task is only about flight search, prefer `CHROME_Search_And_Sort_Flight_Results` instead.\n- Image: `Images/travel_search_surface.png`\n\n### 2. Open The Travel Filter Or Sort Controls\n\n- On hotel, car-rental, or vendor booking pages, use the page's own filter drawer, sort button, or constraint chips.\n- Prefer travel-native controls over shopping habits like assuming a left rail or ecommerce sidebar.\n- Image: `Images/travel_filter_controls.png`\n\n### 3. Verify The Requested Constraint On The Live Results Page\n\n- After changing a filter or sort, confirm the selected state is visible as a persistent chip, label, date range, or reordered result list.\n- End only after the result page has returned to a stable, interactive state and still shows the requested constraint.\n- Image: `Images/travel_results_constraint_visible.png`\n\n### 4. Recover From Browser-Level Failure First\n\n- If Chrome shows a Page Unresponsive dialog, resolve the browser dialog before clicking the blocked page behind it.\n- After recovery, re-check whether the requested travel filters or dates still persist before continuing.\n- Image: `Images/travel_page_unresponsive.png`\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Applying this skill too early on plain Google Flights tasks, which pulls the agent away from the simpler flight-specific workflow.\n- Using shopping-style filter assumptions on hotel or booking results pages.\n- Changing travel filters or dates without checking that the selected constraint persisted on the live results surface.\n- Ignoring the browser's Page Unresponsive dialog and continuing to click the frozen page behind it.\n\n## Runtime Assets\n\n- `state_cards.json` carries the richer multiview authoring bundle.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` carries the slimmer runtime-facing card set.",
