      "skillMarkdown": "# GIMP_Adjust_Hue_Saturation_and_Color_Tone\n\n## Overview\n\nUse this skill when the goal is to change an image's hue, saturation, lightness, color tone, or related blend presentation in GIMP. Keep the workflow centered on the Hue-Saturation adjustment and only use mode or opacity controls when the current task explicitly asks for them as part of the color-tone change.\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\n- The task names hue, saturation, lightness, or color tone.\n- The task asks for a color shift or more/less vivid color rather than exposure, threshold, transparency, or layer visibility.\n- The task combines Hue-Saturation values with blend mode or opacity settings for the same color adjustment.\n- The target image is already open and the requested values are known from the current task.\n\n## When To Use Another Skill\n\n- The request is only about brightness/exposure/levels/curves and does not mention Hue-Saturation-style controls.\n- The request is only about layer opacity, transparency, masks, or thresholding.\n- The active dialog is not Hue-Saturation and the task does not require opening it.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### Adjust Hue Saturation And Related Color Tone\n\n1. Open the Hue-Saturation workflow if it is not already open.\n2. In the Hue-Saturation dialog, enter the current task's requested Hue, Lightness, and Saturation values. If the task uses \"brightness\" while explicitly asking for Hue-Saturation, treat that as the dialog's Lightness-style control only when the wording supports that mapping.\n3. Check the preview while the dialog is open. The canvas should change in the intended color-tone direction, but the screenshot's example colors are not reusable targets.\n4. If the current task also requests a blend mode or opacity for the color adjustment, move to the visible mode/opacity controls after the color values are present and set the requested values there.\n5. Confirm the adjustment only after the requested color values and any requested blend settings match the current task.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nUse `runtime_state_cards.json` as the compact card set for the OSWorld Agent branch. Use `state_cards.json` when auditing or debugging card quality.\n\nLoad only the image card whose `when_to_use` text matches the current screenshot:\n\n- `Images/hue_saturation_dialog_open.png`: entry cue for the Hue-Saturation dialog being open and ready for value entry.\n- `Images/color_values_entered.png`: operation cue for Hue, Lightness, and Saturation values already present in the dialog.\n- `Images/color_tone_blend_confirmed.png`: verification cue for the post-dialog workspace where mode and opacity controls should be checked if the task requested them.\n\nRed boxes indicate interaction targets, such as a value field or mode/opacity control. Green boxes indicate state or verification cues. Use them to recognize equivalent UI regions, not as fixed coordinates.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy any numeric values from the screenshots unless the current task asks for the same values.\n- Do not copy the example image content, file title, layer name, desktop icons, preview colors, or window geometry.\n- Do not treat the right-side mode/opacity area as success unless the current task actually requested those settings and the visible values match.\n- Do not use a changed-looking canvas alone as proof of completion when the task also specified exact Hue-Saturation, mode, or opacity values.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The Hue-Saturation dialog contains the requested Hue, Lightness, and Saturation values before confirmation.\n- Preview remains useful for detecting a color-tone change, but exact example colors are not required.\n- If mode or opacity is requested, the visible controls show the requested mode and opacity before the task is considered complete.\n- The final canvas should reflect the intended color-tone shift without substituting unrelated brightness, exposure, threshold, or transparency-only operations.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Using exposure, brightness, or levels controls when the request specifically names hue or saturation.\n- Treating a transparency-only opacity request as a Hue-Saturation task.\n- Applying blend mode or opacity before entering the Hue-Saturation values.\n- Declaring success from the final screenshot solely because the canvas color changed, without checking requested numeric and blend settings.",
