      "skillMarkdown": "# GIMP_GIMP_Apply_Blur_GEGL_and_Artistic_Filters\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\n- The task names a blur, artistic filter, or GEGL operation in GIMP.\n- The task asks for effect parameters such as radius, threshold, edge preservation, mask radius, mode, or opacity inside the filter workflow.\n- The target image is already open and the requested filter values are known from the task.\n\n## When This Skill Is Not A Good Fit\n\n- The request is about non-filter editing such as painting, selection tools, layer management, or export only.\n- The task is finished once the filter has already been applied and no dialog state remains to verify.\n- The current screen is not a GIMP filter dialog or GEGL Operation window.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- detailed cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- The compact runtime cards for the Agent branch live in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Load only the card whose `when_to_use` matches the current screenshot. Do not load all image cards by default.\n- If a procedure below names an image, treat it as an example state cue. At runtime, use only the matching image card for the current screen.\n- Red boxes mark likely interaction targets. Green boxes mark dialog or state cues to verify before continuing.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not reuse any example coordinates, box positions, crop layout, or window placement.\n- Do not copy example filter names, file names, preview images, or numeric values unless the current task explicitly asks for the same thing.\n- Use the screenshots to recognize the right dialog state and to verify completion cues, not as literal click recipes.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### Apply The Requested Filter\n\n1. Open the named filter workflow in GIMP. Use the classic filter dialog for ordinary blur or artistic filters, and use the GEGL Operation dialog only when the task explicitly calls for GEGL.\n2. Keep the dialog open while entering the requested effect parameters.\n3. If the same dialog includes blend controls such as mode or opacity, set those before confirming the effect.\n4. Confirm the filter only after the visible fields in the active dialog match the task request.\n\n## Image-Grounded States\n\n### Entry Cue: Filter Dialog Open\n\n- Image reference: `Images/filter_dialog_open.png`\n- Use when a classic named filter dialog is open and you are about to enter values.\n\n### Operation Cue: Filter Parameters Entered\n\n- Image reference: `Images/filter_parameters_entered.png`\n- Use when the classic filter dialog stays open and some requested values are already filled in.\n\n### Operation Cue: GEGL Operation Ready\n\n- Image reference: `Images/gegl_operation_ready.png`\n- Use when the task is working through the generic GEGL Operation window rather than a named classic filter dialog.\n\n### Verification Cue: Artistic Filter Ready To Confirm\n\n- Image reference: `Images/artistic_filter_blend_confirmed.png`\n- Use when an artistic filter dialog shows both effect settings and blend settings ready for final confirmation.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The correct filter dialog is still open for the intended effect.\n- The requested effect parameters are visible in the active dialog before pressing `OK`.\n- When the workflow includes blend controls, the same dialog also shows the requested mode or opacity.\n- The matching runtime card confirms the dialog state you are about to act on or finish from.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Opening a similarly named filter instead of the requested one.\n- Using the generic GEGL Operation window when the task actually expects a classic named filter dialog, or the reverse.\n- Confirming the filter after setting only part of the requested numeric values.\n- Forgetting blend mode or opacity settings that belong to the same filter dialog.",
