      "skillMarkdown": "# GIMP_Select_Isolate_and_Fill_Image_Regions\n\n## Overview\n\nUse this skill when an image is already open in GIMP and the requested edit must stay inside one local region such as clothing, a background area, or another object boundary.\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\n- The task asks you to isolate a local region before changing its color or applying a fill.\n- The requested change should affect part of the image, not the full canvas.\n- The workflow depends on choosing or using a selection tool such as Free Select or Scissors Select before the recolor.\n\n## When Not To Use It\n\n- The task is a full-image recolor or another edit that does not depend on an active selection.\n- The task is primarily a threshold, color-pick, or color-to-alpha operation rather than a boundary-based selection and fill.\n- The image is not yet open in GIMP.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- The target image is already open in GIMP.\n- The region to isolate is visible on the canvas.\n- The requested replacement color, fill, or gradient is known before you commit the final recolor.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\ndetailed cards live in `state_cards.json`. The compact runtime cards for the Agent branch live in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n\n- Load only the card whose `when_to_use` conditions match the current screenshot. Do not load unrelated image cards just because the task sounds similar.\n- Use red boxes as interaction cues and green boxes as state or verification cues.\n- Treat every box as non-transferable. They show what mattered in the example image and are never reusable coordinates.\n- Keep this skill text-first: the image cards help with state recognition and verification, but the procedure still governs the action sequence.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy the example subject, object shape, panel placement, or canvas framing into a new task.\n- Do not copy the example fill color unless the current task explicitly asks for that same color.\n- Do not assume the same selection tool is always correct. Match the tool to the current request.\n- Do not use any boxed area as a click target by position. Find the equivalent UI element or result in the live screenshot.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### 1. Open the correct selection state\n\nIf the target region is not isolated yet, open the appropriate selection tool and prepare to trace the boundary before any fill is applied.\n\nReference image: `Images/selection_tool_ready.png`\n\nUse this visual only when the current screen still shows the tool-selection stage. At runtime, load the matching card from `runtime_state_cards.json`; use the full card in `state_cards.json` only for audit-level inspection.\n\n### 2. Isolate the requested local region\n\nTrace or otherwise establish the boundary of the garment, background area, or object that should change. The exact tracing method depends on the requested tool and the image content.\n\n### 3. Apply the requested fill or recolor inside the active selection\n\nUse the requested solid color, gradient, or fill operation only after the target region is selected.\n\n### 4. Verify the localized result\n\nCheck that the intended region changed and the rest of the image stayed intact.\n\nReference image: `Images/selection_fill_result.png`\n\nThis image is a verification example, not a template for the subject, region shape, or final color.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The changed pixels are confined to the intended local region.\n- The surrounding image remains visually unchanged.\n- The fill or recolor follows the selected boundary closely enough for the task.\n- The final result matches the requested type of change, such as solid color versus gradient.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Choosing a paint or draw tool instead of a selection tool, which causes the edit to spill outside the target region.\n- Applying the fill before the selection is complete.\n- Verifying only that some color changed, without checking whether unrelated parts of the image also changed.\n- Treating the example screenshot as a requirement to match the same subject, color, or tool layout.",
      "runtimeSchema": "2026-04-17.runtime_state_bundles.v4",
