      "failureModes": [
        "Resizing the canvas before the transform is applied, which makes later geometry alignment harder.",
        "Changing geometry on the wrong target because a tool state carried over from a previous edit.",
        "Confusing canvas size with image size and unintentionally resampling the image instead of just changing document bounds."
      ],
      "skillMarkdown": "# GIMP_GIMP_Transform_Image_Geometry_and_Canvas\n\n## Overview\n\nApply the requested geometric transform first, then adjust the canvas size if the task requires a new document boundary after the transform.\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\n- When the user requests rotation, shear, flip, or perspective changes to the image geometry.\n- When the task also asks for a new canvas size after the transform.\n- When the geometry change should preserve the transformed image inside a resized canvas.\n- When the transform result needs to be visible before deciding the final canvas bounds.\n\nDo not use this skill for plain crop workflows, for Image Size / resampling tasks that change pixel dimensions directly, or for canvas-only changes when no geometry transform is requested.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- The source image is open.\n- The transform angle or geometric values are known.\n- The target canvas dimensions are known if the canvas must also be resized.\n\n## Atomic Capabilities\n\n- **Apply Geometric Transform**: Use the rotation or related transform workflow on the current image.\n- Derived from: Rotate Shear Flip Or Perspective Transform\n- **Resize The Canvas Afterwards**: Open the canvas-size workflow after the transform result is in place.\n- Derived from: Resize Canvas Dimensions\n\n## Decision Guide\n\n- If `The task asks for a rotate, shear, flip, or perspective change.`, choose `Apply Geometric Transform`. The transform should happen before any canvas resize so the geometry change is visible first.\n- If `The user also specifies new canvas width and height.`, choose `Resize The Canvas Afterwards`. Canvas size is a separate document-boundary step that should follow the transform.\n\n## Visual Annotation Conventions\n\n- Red boxes mark the interactive target that should be clicked, typed into, or otherwise manipulated.\n- Green boxes mark the state signal or result change that the agent should verify before continuing.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nThis skill has two image-card files:\n\n- `state_cards.json`: full detailed version with detailed transfer limits, review rationale, and grounding metadata.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json`: compact version for the Agent branch prompt budget.\n\nLoad only the card or cards whose `when_to_use` conditions match the current GIMP screenshot. The runtime branch should not preload unrelated image cards just because they belong to this skill.\n\n- Use cards for state recognition, applicability checks, and result verification.\n- Do not use cards as coordinate recipes; red and green boxes are visual cues, not reusable click positions.\n- If a card's `when_not_to_use` condition applies, ignore that image and continue from the text procedure or another matching card.\n- Treat `non_transferable_parts` in `state_cards.json` as hard transfer limits: literal example values, page content, image subjects, object positions, filenames, and numeric settings should not be copied unless the current task asks for them.\n\n## State Card Index\n\n- `Images/canvas_size_dialog_open.png` -> `canvas_size_dialog_open`: operation_state / state_cue for Canvas Size Dialog Open.\n- `Images/transform_dialog_active.png` -> `transform_dialog_active`: entry_state / state_cue for Transform Dialog Active.\n- `Images/transform_ready_to_confirm.png` -> `transform_ready_to_confirm`: verification_state / verification_cue for Transform Ready To Confirm.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- The example angle and the example canvas dimensions in the screenshots are not defaults. Always use the values requested by the current task.\n- The sample image content, layer names, checkerboard extents, and dialog placement are screenshot-specific evidence, not reusable goals.\n- A red box identifies the kind of control to use, not a fixed pixel coordinate.\n- A green box identifies the state to recognize or verify, not a promise that the same region will be in the same location on another machine.\n\n## Procedures\n\n### Transform The Image And Then Resize The Canvas\n\n1. Start the requested geometry transform on the current image.\n   - Use the matching transform workflow for the task, such as rotate, shear, flip, or perspective.\n   - If the screen matches `Images/transform_dialog_active.png`, use that card to confirm you are still in the editable pre-commit transform state.\n\n2. Enter the requested transform value and inspect the live preview.\n   - Keep attention on the transform controls until the requested value is fully entered.\n   - Do not resize the canvas yet.\n\n3. Verify the transform result is now the working image state.\n   - If the screen matches `Images/transform_ready_to_confirm.png`, treat it as the visual checkpoint that the image has already changed orientation on the checkerboard canvas and the workflow is ready to proceed.\n   - The practical verification cue is the committed rotated result, not the literal sample angle from the screenshot.\n\n4. Open the canvas-size workflow only after the geometry change is in place.\n   - If the screen matches `Images/canvas_size_dialog_open.png`, use that card to confirm the correct dialog is open.\n\n5. Enter the requested canvas width and height, adjust placement if needed, then confirm the resize.\n   - Stay in Canvas Size, not Image Size, when the task is about document bounds rather than resampling.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The image visibly reflects the requested geometry change before any canvas-size adjustment begins.\n- The transform workflow is no longer waiting for value entry when you move into the canvas step.\n- The canvas-size dialog refers to the already transformed image, not the original untransformed state.\n- After the resize, the document bounds match the requested canvas dimensions and the transformed content remains positioned as intended.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Resizing the canvas before the transform is applied, which makes later geometry alignment harder.\n- Changing geometry on the wrong target because a tool state carried over from a previous edit.\n- Confusing canvas size with image size and unintentionally resampling the image instead of just changing document bounds.\n- Treating the example numeric values from the screenshots as reusable defaults instead of task-specific placeholders.",
