      "skillMarkdown": "# Arrange and Format Slide Objects\n\n## Overview\n\nKeep the intended object selected, make geometry or appearance changes from the Properties sidebar, and verify the result directly on the slide before moving on.\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\n- Use this skill when a slide object already exists and the task is to move it, resize it, rotate it, flip it, layer it, crop it, or restyle it.\n- Use it when the requested result can be checked from the selected object on the canvas or from object-specific settings in the Properties sidebar.\n- Do not use it for inserting a brand-new object or for slide-wide formatting that does not depend on a selected object.\n- Do not use it as the main skill just because the instruction mentions a slide number. If the real work is text formatting, background changes, or notes editing, this skill is only secondary if an object is actually being manipulated.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- The target object is visible on the current slide.\n- You can select the object that the task refers to.\n- The requested change has a visible result on the canvas or in the object's Properties controls.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- Audit detail lives in `state_cards.json`.\n- The prompt-budget runtime copy for the Agent branch lives in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Load only the card or cards whose screenshot state matches the current LibreOffice Impress surface. Do not load every image by default.\n- Treat red boxes as interaction cues and green boxes as state or verification cues. They identify what kind of element matters, not a coordinate to replay.\n- If the visible UI does not match a card's `when_to_use` conditions, ignore that card and continue from the text procedure.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy example image subjects, slide text, filenames, slide numbers, or displayed numeric values unless the current task explicitly asks for them.\n- Do not reuse red or green box positions as click targets.\n- Transfer the relationship between object selection, the relevant Properties section, and the result verification state.\n- The runtime should load only matching image cards even if the procedure text references an image example.\n\n## Entry Checks\n\n1. Confirm the correct slide in the navigator.\n2. Select the exact target object and verify resize handles or another object-selection signal are visible.\n3. Confirm that the Properties sidebar belongs to that selected object rather than to slide or text settings.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### arrange_or_style_object\n\n1. If the task needs exact placement, size, rotation, flip, layering, or alignment, use the geometry controls shown in `Images/object_geometry_controls.png` as the reference state for the relevant Properties section.\n2. If the task needs a shadow or another appearance change, use `Images/object_visual_effects.png` as the reference state for finding the correct styling controls in Properties.\n3. Apply only the changes requested for the current object.\n4. Check the finished object on the slide canvas before leaving the slide. Use `Images/object_result_state.png` only as a verification-style example, and load its runtime card only when the current surface matches that completion state.\n\n## Failure Recovery\n\n- If the wrong object becomes selected, stop and reselect the intended object before editing any field.\n- If the object selection disappears while you are typing numeric values, reselect the object and verify the change belongs to the correct object before continuing.\n- If the sidebar shows slide or text properties instead of object properties, return to the canvas and re-establish object selection.\n- Do not leave the slide after changing a property field until the object result is visible on the canvas.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The correct object is still selected when you inspect the result.\n- The object's position, size, layering, rotation, crop, or appearance now matches the task request.\n- If the task specified a property value that remains visible in Properties, that value agrees with the visual result on the slide.\n- The final state is confirmed on the object itself, not inferred from the example screenshot content.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Editing the wrong object because selection changed on the canvas.\n- Using slide or text properties when the task is object-specific.\n- Applying an appearance effect when the task only asked for geometry changes, or the reverse.\n- Treating slide targeting as enough and never verifying the object-level result on the requested slide.\n- Ending the task before verifying the visible result on the selected object.",
