      "skillMarkdown": "# Review, Summarize, and Rewrite Slide Content\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\nUse this skill when the task depends on existing slide content and asks you to rewrite, replace, condense, or summarize that content inside the current deck.\n\n- Use it for exact word or phrase swaps, paragraph rewrites, and summary text inserted from material already present in the presentation.\n- Prefer a different skill for pure formatting-only changes, object layout changes, or creating unrelated new content that does not come from the deck.\n\n## Core Procedure\n\n1. Read the relevant source slide content and identify the destination slide or text region.\n2. Choose the editing surface that fits the task:\n   - direct text editing on the slide when a textbox or paragraph region is already the target\n   - Find and Replace when the job is an exact wording substitution\n   - a prepared or newly added textbox when the task asks for a rewritten summary on a specific slide\n3. Enter only the wording and formatting constraints that the current task explicitly requires.\n4. Verify the visible result on the intended slide before leaving it.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- `state_cards.json` is the audit-friendly image card file.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact version intended for runtime branch loading.\n- Keep this skill text-first. Load only the runtime card whose `when_to_use` and visible cues match the current screenshot. If no screenshot matches, continue from the text procedure instead of forcing an image match.\n- Existing image references below are examples of recognizable states. They are not a requirement to load every image or to follow a fixed screenshot sequence.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Red boxes indicate interaction targets. Green boxes indicate state or verification cues.\n- Neither red nor green boxes are reusable coordinates.\n- Do not copy example slide titles, paragraph text, artwork, box sizes, or example formatting values from the screenshots unless the current task explicitly asks for those same details.\n- Treat image cards as UI-state grounding only. The transferable part is the editing situation, not the literal content shown in the example deck.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The correct slide thumbnail is still selected.\n- The intended text region now shows the rewritten or summarized wording.\n- For exact replacements, the old wording is no longer visible where the task said it should change.\n- If the task specifies visible formatting, such as a font size or color, verify it from the canvas or sidebar before finishing.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Editing the wrong slide because the selected thumbnail changed.\n- Typing into the wrong textbox or placeholder.\n- Using Find and Replace for a task that really needed direct local editing, or missing Find and Replace when the task is an exact term swap.\n- Reusing example wording from a screenshot instead of writing the content required by the current task.\n- Leaving the slide before checking that the requested result is visibly present.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### rewrite_or_summarize_existing_content\n\n- Open a rewrite surface that matches the task. For exact text substitution, a matching state is shown in `Images/rewrite_surface_open.png`.\n- When the target slide and text region are active, enter the rewritten or summarized text directly on the canvas. A matching state is shown in `Images/rewrite_text_entry.png`.\n- Before finishing, confirm the final visible result on the target slide. A matching verification state is shown in `Images/rewrite_result_state.png`.\n\nOnly load the image card whose cues match the current screen. Use `state_cards.json` for auditing and `runtime_state_cards.json` for compact runtime grounding.",
