      "id": "OS_Archive_Extract_and_Convert_Files_in_Terminal",
      "name": "Archive Extract and Convert Files in Terminal",
      "description": "Create archives, extract compressed files, or convert document outputs in Terminal and verify the produced file or folder exists at the expected path.",
      "domain": "os",
      "domainLabel": "Ubuntu OS",
      "platform": "Ubuntu",
      "category": "GUI Tasks",
      "sourcePath": "ubuntu/os/OS_Archive_Extract_and_Convert_Files_in_Terminal",
      "imageCount": 6,
      "stateCardCount": 3,
      "runtimeCardCount": 3,
      "planStepCount": 7,
      "tags": [
        "terminal",
        "files",
        "documents"
      ],
      "overview": "Use this skill for text-first Ubuntu tasks where the main work happens in Terminal: creating an archive, extracting a compressed file, or producing a converted output from a shell command. It is a fit when success must be shown through visible terminal state such as a completed command, a returned prompt, or output that names the produced file or folder.",
      "applicability": [],
      "failureModes": [
        "Running the right kind of command in the wrong directory.",
        "Reusing example filenames from the screenshots instead of the live task values.",
        "Treating a typed command as success without checking visible output."
      ],
      "skillMarkdown": "# Archive Extract and Convert Files in Terminal\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\nUse this skill for text-first Ubuntu tasks where the main work happens in Terminal: creating an archive, extracting a compressed file, or producing a converted output from a shell command. It is a fit when success must be shown through visible terminal state such as a completed command, a returned prompt, or output that names the produced file or folder.\n\nUse another skill when the task is mainly a GUI archive manager flow, when the destination file must be validated in a different application, or when the task is not fundamentally a terminal workflow.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Terminal is open, or the current desktop state allows Terminal to be opened directly.\n- The task provides enough concrete information to run and verify the shell action: target path, filename, archive name, conversion target, password, or output name.\n\n## Core Procedure\n\n1. Prepare the terminal context.\n   - Open or focus Terminal.\n   - Move to the working directory that contains the source file or is required for the output path.\n   - If the task starts from a desktop state, [`Images/os_archive_extract_and_convert_files_in_terminal_prepare_terminal_context.png`](Images/os_archive_extract_and_convert_files_in_terminal_prepare_terminal_context.png) is the setup reference. It is a desktop-before-command cue, not a completion cue.\n2. Run the requested archive, extract, or conversion command.\n   - Type the exact command needed for the live task.\n   - Recheck the path, source name, output name, and any flags before pressing Enter.\n   - [`Images/os_archive_extract_and_convert_files_in_terminal_run_requested_command.png`](Images/os_archive_extract_and_convert_files_in_terminal_run_requested_command.png) shows the right kind of operation-state match: a focused terminal, visible working directory, and the command line in view.\n3. Verify the result from visible terminal evidence.\n   - Look for tool-specific success output, a returned prompt, and the expected file or folder name.\n   - If the command itself does not make the result explicit, run a follow-up listing or inspection command so the output is visible on screen.\n   - [`Images/os_archive_extract_and_convert_files_in_terminal_verify_terminal_result.png`](Images/os_archive_extract_and_convert_files_in_terminal_verify_terminal_result.png) is the main verification reference.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- [`state_cards.json`](state_cards.json) is the detailed version with full image-level reasoning.\n- [`runtime_state_cards.json`](runtime_state_cards.json) is the compact branch-loading version.\n- Load only the card or cards whose `when_to_use` conditions match the current screenshot. Do not load the whole image set by default.\n- Treat red boxes as interaction cues and green boxes as verification cues. They show what matters in the example image, not reusable coordinates.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy example filenames, paths, passwords, or output names from the screenshots unless the live task explicitly asks for those exact values.\n- Do not rely on wallpaper, icon arrangement, terminal size, or box placement. Those are incidental to the captured example.\n- The first image is only a setup-state cue. It does not prove the shell is in the right directory.\n- The second image shows the command-entry pattern, but not a durable completion signal by itself.\n- The third image shows a strong terminal-side completion pattern, but the exact success text depends on the tool being used.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The command finishes and the shell prompt returns.\n- Terminal output names the created archive, extracted folder, or converted file.\n- There is no visible error output.\n- If success is ambiguous, a follow-up command such as a directory listing makes the result visible in Terminal before completion is reported.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Running the right kind of command in the wrong directory.\n- Reusing example filenames from the screenshots instead of the live task values.\n- Treating a typed command as success without checking visible output.\n- Stopping at a password prompt or partial output before the command actually completes.",
