      "skillMarkdown": "# Configure Dock and Desktop Layout\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\nUse this skill when the task asks for a dock, desktop, or Files preference that is normally changed from Ubuntu `Settings > Appearance` or from the relevant `Files Preferences` surface, and success depends on a visible control state rather than a hidden side effect.\n\nTypical fits include:\n\n- dock visibility or edge behavior\n- desktop icon size or desktop item visibility\n- Files behavior that changes how folders or items open from the desktop\n- any similar layout preference that can be verified from the control row after the change\n\nDo not use this skill for unrelated Settings categories, default application changes, search-provider changes, or file-management tasks that do not end in a persistent dock or desktop preference.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nThis package keeps two card sets:\n\n- `state_cards.json` is the full detailed version with detailed transfer limits and review rationale.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact version intended for Agent or OSWorld branch loading.\n\nRuntime should load only the cards whose `when_to_use` conditions plausibly match the current screenshot. Do not preload all four images as if they were a fixed sequence.\n\nThe preserved images are mixed-strength cues:\n\n- `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_open_settings_surface.png` is a broad desktop entry state.\n- `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_locate_target_control.png` is a shell-level top-bar cue before Settings is open.\n- `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_apply_requested_setting.png` is a Settings-navigation cue from the wrong page.\n- `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_verify_result_state.png` is only supplemental desktop-aftermath context, not strong proof on its own.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\nTreat the images as state-recognition aids, not coordinate recipes.\n\n- Red boxes are interaction cues only.\n- Green boxes, when present in other skills, are verification cues only.\n- Neither color gives reusable coordinates.\n\nIgnore source-specific details such as wallpaper art, desktop filenames, icon placement, open application titles, the current time, and unrelated Settings values. Several preserved screenshots show generic desktop context or an unrelated Settings page; those details are not the requested result and should not be copied into runtime decisions.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Reach the correct configuration surface.\n   - If the task starts from the desktop, open or focus Ubuntu Settings by whatever visible entry point is available in the current environment.\n   - If Settings is already open on the wrong page, use the sidebar or search field to reach `Appearance` or the relevant `Files Preferences` surface.\n   - Image references: `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_open_settings_surface.png`, `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_locate_target_control.png`, `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_apply_requested_setting.png`\n\n2. Locate the exact control row.\n   - Match the row label and control type before interacting.\n   - Nearby toggles, dropdowns, and radio-style selectors can look similar, so confirm the text label first.\n\n3. Apply the requested value.\n   - Change only the named dock or desktop preference.\n   - If the page is still wrong or the control row is missing, go back to navigation instead of guessing.\n\n4. Verify the result from the strongest visible cue available.\n   - Best verification is the requested toggle, selector, or dropdown still showing the requested state in the relevant Settings or Files Preferences row.\n   - Use `Images/os_configure_dock_and_desktop_layout_verify_result_state.png` only when the current task truly ends in a desktop-visible aftermath and the screenshot actually matches that context.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\nPrefer these verification signals, in order:\n\n1. The exact requested control remains visibly set in `Appearance` or `Files Preferences`.\n2. If the task changes the desktop shell itself, the desktop view reflects the requested behavior and does not contradict the control state.\n3. If the desktop view is ambiguous, reopen the configuration surface and verify the control directly before marking success.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Acting on the wrong Settings page because an unrelated page happened to be open already.\n- Clicking a neighboring toggle or selector without confirming the row label.\n- Treating a shell-level screenshot or generic desktop screenshot as proof that the requested preference was set.\n- Leaving Settings before confirming that the requested state persists on the relevant control row.",
