      "skillMarkdown": "# Configure Multitasking and Hot Corner\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\n- Use this skill for Ubuntu Settings tasks that explicitly target the `Multitasking` panel.\n- Typical requests include enabling or disabling `Hot Corner`, switching between dynamic and fixed workspaces, adjusting workspace count, or changing another control that remains visible on the same panel.\n- Use it when success depends on a visible state that can be checked directly in Settings before exiting.\n- Do not use it for neighboring Settings categories such as `Notifications`, `Privacy`, or `Displays`.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- `state_cards.json` is the detailed version with full per-image rationale.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact version intended for runtime branch loading.\n- Runtime should load only the card or cards that plausibly match the current screenshot, not the entire image set by default.\n- Red boxes are interaction cues. Green boxes are verification cues. Neither is a reusable coordinate map.\n- Two preserved images are weak desktop entry cues; the Multitasking panel is only clearly shown in the apply and verify cards.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Treat wallpapers, desktop icons, dock contents, window size, and surrounding clutter as example-only context.\n- Do not copy the visible workspace count, radio selection, or Hot Corner state from the images unless the current task asks for that exact result.\n- If a card does not show the requested control row, use it only as a coarse state cue and fall back to the text procedure.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Open Ubuntu Settings and navigate to `Multitasking` through the sidebar or Settings search. `Images/os_configure_multitasking_and_hot_corner_open_settings_surface.png` and `Images/os_configure_multitasking_and_hot_corner_locate_target_control.png` are only entry cues for the pre-Settings desktop state.\n2. On the `Multitasking` panel, read the requested row label carefully so you do not drift to a neighboring control such as `Active Screen Edges` instead of `Hot Corner`.\n3. Apply the requested toggle, selector, or numeric value. `Images/os_configure_multitasking_and_hot_corner_apply_requested_setting.png` is the strongest action reference because it clearly shows the `Multitasking` page with editable controls in view.\n4. Stay on the same panel and confirm the requested state persists visually. `Images/os_configure_multitasking_and_hot_corner_verify_result_state.png` is the main verification reference.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- `Multitasking` remains selected in the Settings sidebar.\n- The requested row shows the correct toggle position, radio selection, dropdown value, or enabled or disabled stepper state.\n- If one selection changes another row's availability, verify both the primary setting and the dependent enabled or disabled state before finishing.\n- When an image card matches, use `runtime_state_cards.json` for branch loading and `state_cards.json` for deeper audit detail.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Acting on a nearby control because the row label was not re-read before clicking.\n- Copying the example state from an image instead of the state requested by the current task.\n- Treating the desktop-only entry cards as proof that Settings or `Multitasking` is already open.\n- Leaving the panel before the requested state is visibly stable.",
