      "skillMarkdown": "# Configure Removable Media\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\n- Use this skill when the task asks for a change inside Ubuntu Settings on the `Removable Media` page.\n- Use it for media-type dropdown rows, the insertion-policy checkbox, or controls inside `Other Media...` when the result must still be visible in Settings.\n- Use it when success depends on reading the final value from the panel, not on assuming the click succeeded.\n\n## Text-First Procedure\n\n1. Open Ubuntu Settings.\n2. Reach `Removable Media` through the sidebar or Settings search.\n3. Bring the requested row or checkbox into view and read its label carefully before changing anything.\n4. Change only the control named in the task.\n5. Verify that the same labeled control still shows the requested state before leaving the page.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- detailed cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- Compact runtime cards for the Agent branch live in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Load only the cards whose `when_to_use` conditions match the live screenshot. Do not preload all cards just because they exist in the package.\n- The runtime set includes both actionable panel references and desktop-only rejection cues. If a desktop card matches, keep navigating; it is evidence that `Removable Media` is not open yet.\n- Image references below are support for state recognition. They are not coordinate recipes.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Red boxes indicate interaction cues. Green boxes indicate verification cues.\n- Treat every box as a hint about which object matters, never as a reusable position.\n- Do not transfer the example dropdown values from the screenshots unless the current task asks for the same literal value.\n- Desktop wallpaper, document names, top-bar time, and icon layout are incidental and should not drive matching.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The Settings window is still on `Removable Media`.\n- The row label named in the task is still aligned with the edited control.\n- The requested dropdown value or checkbox state remains visible after the action.\n- For insertion-policy tasks, verify the checkbox itself rather than inferring the state from surrounding text.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Stopping on the Ubuntu desktop and assuming the target Settings surface has already been reached.\n- Opening Settings but editing a neighboring row because several dropdowns look alike.\n- Verifying the wrong row because the selected value looks plausible.\n- Leaving the panel before the requested value or checkbox state is visibly persisted.\n\n## Procedures\n\n### Reach Removable Media\n\nTrigger:\n- The task refers to removable-media behavior, but the current screenshot is not yet the `Removable Media` page.\n\nAction:\n- Open Ubuntu Settings, then navigate to `Removable Media` through the sidebar or Settings search.\n\nImage support:\n- `Images/os_configure_removable_media_open_settings_surface.png`\n- `Images/os_configure_removable_media_locate_target_control.png`\n\nRuntime note:\n- These two preserved images are desktop non-match cues. If one matches, continue navigating until a real Settings view is on screen.\n\n### Apply The Requested Change\n\nTrigger:\n- `Removable Media` is open and the requested row or checkbox is visible.\n\nAction:\n- Anchor on the row label first, then change only the adjacent dropdown or checkbox named by the task.\n\nImage support:\n- `Images/os_configure_removable_media_apply_requested_setting.png`\n\nRuntime note:\n- Load this card only when the live screen matches the panel layout and the task is still in the action step.\n\n### Verify The Persisted Result\n\nTrigger:\n- The control has already been changed and the final state should still be readable from the panel.\n\nAction:\n- Confirm that the exact requested row or checkbox remains visibly set before finishing.\n\nImage support:\n- `Images/os_configure_removable_media_verify_result_state.png`\n\nRuntime note:\n- Load only the matching verification card from `runtime_state_cards.json`. The example boxed value is a verification pattern, not a default target state.",
