      "skillMarkdown": "# Control Processes and Application Sessions in Terminal\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\nUse this skill when the task is primarily a Terminal workflow and the success condition can be checked from visible shell output. Typical fits include starting or stopping an app from Terminal, listing processes, checking resource-related process state, or confirming that a target process appears or disappears after a command.\n\nDo not use this skill when the task is mainly a GUI settings flow, when the required action happens in another app surface, or when terminal output is not the task-visible completion cue.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Terminal is open or can be opened directly.\n- The task names a concrete target such as a process, package, path, account, or session-related result that can be checked on screen.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### 1. Prepare the terminal context\n\nBring Terminal to the foreground or open it if the desktop is still visible. Make sure you are in the right shell context before entering the task command.\n\nImage reference:\n- `Images/os_control_processes_and_application_sessions_in_terminal_prepare_terminal_context.png`\n\n### 2. Run the requested command\n\nType the exact process or session command needed for the current task, then execute it. Keep the command specific to the target the task names.\n\nImage reference:\n- `Images/os_control_processes_and_application_sessions_in_terminal_run_requested_command.png`\n\n### 3. Verify the terminal result\n\nRead the visible terminal output and confirm it proves the requested state. The task is complete only when the output matches the current target, not when the example screenshot looks similar.\n\nImage reference:\n- `Images/os_control_processes_and_application_sessions_in_terminal_verify_terminal_result.png`\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- `state_cards.json` is the full detailed reference file. Use it when you need the detailed per-image rationale, transfer limits, and source evidence.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact output for the Agent branch. Runtime should load only the card whose `when_to_use` and visible cues match the current screenshot.\n- Image references in this skill are examples of reusable states. They are not a requirement to load every card at once.\n- Red boxes are interaction cues. Green boxes are verification cues. Neither should be treated as reusable coordinates.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy the example machine's usernames, hostnames, directories, process names, app names, PIDs, desktop files, or wallpaper.\n- Do not reuse literal command strings from a screenshot unless the current task explicitly asks for that exact target.\n- Treat the images as state examples for when to act and what to verify, not as templates for fixed screen layout.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The terminal returns to an editable prompt after the command completes.\n- Visible output explicitly supports the requested state, such as the target process being listed, not listed, started, stopped, or otherwise confirmed.\n- There is no contradictory output showing the command failed or the wrong target was affected.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Running a plausible command against the wrong process, application, path, or shell context.\n- Treating a typed command as success before checking the resulting output.\n- Reusing example literals from a screenshot instead of the target named in the current task.\n- Finishing after the prompt returns without checking whether the terminal evidence actually proves the requested state.",
