      "id": "OS_Manage_Bluetooth_Settings",
      "name": "Manage Bluetooth Settings",
      "description": "Navigate Ubuntu Settings to the Bluetooth page, reason about adapter status, toggle the Bluetooth master switch when available, and verify the visible final Bluetooth state.",
      "domain": "os",
      "domainLabel": "Ubuntu OS",
      "platform": "Ubuntu",
      "category": "GUI Tasks",
      "sourcePath": "ubuntu/os/OS_Manage_Bluetooth_Settings",
      "imageCount": 8,
      "stateCardCount": 4,
      "runtimeCardCount": 4,
      "planStepCount": 7,
      "tags": [
        "ubuntu os"
      ],
      "overview": "The task explicitly targets Bluetooth settings, Bluetooth state, or the Bluetooth master switch in Ubuntu Settings. The result can be verified from the Bluetooth page itself rather than from a generic quick-settings popover.",
      "applicability": [
        "The task explicitly targets Bluetooth settings, Bluetooth state, or the Bluetooth master switch in Ubuntu Settings.",
        "The result can be verified from the Bluetooth page itself rather than from a generic quick-settings popover.",
        "The task explicitly targets Bluetooth settings, Bluetooth state, or the Bluetooth master switch in Ubuntu Settings."
      ],
      "failureModes": [
        "Treating the Bluetooth status text as if it were the toggle itself.",
        "Looping on a disabled switch even after the page already says no adapter is available.",
        "Forcing a battery or power workflow onto the Bluetooth page."
      ],
      "skillMarkdown": "# Manage Bluetooth Settings\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\n- The task explicitly targets Bluetooth settings, Bluetooth state, or the Bluetooth master switch in Ubuntu Settings.\n- The result can be verified from the Bluetooth page itself rather than from a generic quick-settings popover.\n\n## Text-First Procedure\n\n1. Open Ubuntu Settings and navigate to the Bluetooth page.\n2. Read the visible adapter or status text before deciding whether the task is about a status report or the master switch.\n3. If the master switch is visible and enabled, set it to the requested state and stay on the same page for verification.\n4. If the page shows `No Bluetooth Found`, an unavailable adapter, or a disabled non-interactive switch, treat that as a real runtime constraint instead of hallucinating a control that is not there.\n5. Do not keep clicking a disabled toggle or drift into unrelated Settings pages after the Bluetooth page already exposes a blocked state.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- Audit state bundles live in `state_cards.json`.\n- Compact runtime state bundles for the agent branch live in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Load only the states whose `when_to_use` conditions match the current screenshot.\n- Treat the stored images as state evidence only. They are never coordinate templates.\n\nImage references used by this skill:\n\n- `Images/os_manage_bluetooth_settings_open_settings_surface.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_bluetooth_settings_inspect_adapter_status.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_bluetooth_settings_apply_requested_setting.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_bluetooth_settings_verify_result_state.png`\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Reuse the page, prompt, or modal relationship that the image demonstrates, not the literal example values.\n- Red cues mark the local work region. Green cues mark the verification region.\n- Do not transfer example filenames, package names, usernames, desktop contents, timestamps, or wallpaper details unless the live task calls for those exact values.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The relevant page, shell prompt, or modal must still be visible at the end of the workflow.\n- The requested final state must be readable directly from the live UI or shell output.\n- Do not finish from command entry, pre-action page state, or a guessed outcome.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Treating the Bluetooth status text as if it were the toggle itself.\n- Looping on a disabled switch even after the page already says no adapter is available.\n- Forcing a battery or power workflow onto the Bluetooth page.\n- Ignoring a no-adapter state and pretending the task succeeded anyway.\n\n## References\n\n- Audit card set: `state_cards.json`\n- Compact runtime card set: `runtime_state_cards.json`\n- Planning source: `plan.json`",
