      "skillMarkdown": "# Manage Calendar Events\n\n## Overview\n\nUse Ubuntu Calendar to create or edit an event, save it, and verify that the requested details are visible on the correct date before you finish.\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\n- Use this skill when the task asks you to add, edit, or confirm a calendar event in Ubuntu Calendar.\n- The task should already specify the details you need to enter, such as title, date, time, location, or notes.\n- This skill is for the Calendar workflow itself, not for unrelated system settings changes that may appear in source screenshots.\n\n## Text-First Procedure\n\n1. Open Ubuntu Calendar if it is not already open.\n2. Navigate to the requested date and open the event editor for a new or existing event.\n3. Enter only the details requested by the current task, then save or finish the event.\n4. Verify that Calendar shows the saved event on the intended date with the requested details visible.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- Audit-ready image cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- The runtime branch should load compact cards from `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Load only the card whose `when_to_use` matches the current screenshot. Do not preload every image.\n- `Images/os_manage_calendar_events_open_calendar_surface.png` is a launch-entry cue for the desktop-before-Calendar state.\n- `Images/os_manage_calendar_events_enter_event_details.png` is a drift or failure cue: it shows Settings covering Calendar, not a usable event editor.\n- `Images/os_manage_calendar_events_verify_saved_event.png` is the primary post-save verification card.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Treat red boxes as interaction cues and green boxes as result cues only. They are never reusable coordinates.\n- Do not copy example event text, dates, times, locations, notes, timezone labels, desktop files, or window positions from the screenshots unless the current task independently requests the same value.\n- If a screenshot contains unrelated apps or overlays, use that only as a warning about drift, not as a procedure to repeat.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- A saved event should remain visible in Calendar after the save action completes.\n- The visible event should match the current task's requested title, date, time, location, or other specified details.\n- Verify the event on the correct day or date cell before closing the app or ending the task.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- You are still on the Ubuntu desktop and have not opened Calendar yet.\n- Another window, such as Settings, is covering Calendar when you should be editing or verifying the event.\n- The event was saved without checking that it appears on the intended date.\n- The visible event belongs to the example screenshot rather than to the current task's requested details.\n\n## Procedures\n\n### Open Calendar\n\n- If Calendar is not open yet, launch it from the Ubuntu dock or app grid.\n- Image reference: `Images/os_manage_calendar_events_open_calendar_surface.png`\n\n### Enter Or Edit Event Details\n\n- Reach the actual Calendar event editor and fill in the requested fields.\n- If the screen resembles the Settings overlay image instead, recover back to Calendar before typing.\n- Image reference: `Images/os_manage_calendar_events_enter_event_details.png`\n\n### Verify The Saved Event\n\n- Confirm that the saved event is visible in Calendar on the intended date.\n- Match the current task's requested details, not the example values shown in the reference image.\n- Image reference: `Images/os_manage_calendar_events_verify_saved_event.png`",
