      "skillMarkdown": "# Manage Privacy Location Proxy and Connectivity\n\n## When This Skill Is Applicable\n\n- Use this skill for Ubuntu Settings tasks that change a privacy, search, notifications, network, proxy, connectivity, or closely related system control and then require the final state to remain visible.\n- It fits best when the task names a specific row, toggle, selector, or mode that can be verified directly in the Settings content pane.\n- Keep the workflow text-first: open Settings, navigate by sidebar or Settings search, change the named row only, and confirm that the resulting state persists on the main page.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Ubuntu Settings can be opened from the current desktop session.\n- The requested end state is explicit enough to verify from a visible row, selector, or toggle.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- detailed image cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- The Agent branch should load `runtime_state_cards.json` and keep only the cards whose `when_to_use` cues match the current screenshot.\n- This package contains three weak desktop-entry screenshots and one strong in-app verification screenshot. Do not force a desktop-card match once a Settings window is already visible.\n- Red boxes are interaction cues and green boxes are verification cues when they are present. They are never reusable coordinates.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not transfer example page titles, row names, selected apps, top-bar times, wallpaper, desktop file names, or dock order unless the current task explicitly asks for them.\n- The preserved verification example happens on the Search page. Transfer only the pattern \"the changed Settings row remains visible and already shows the requested state\", not the literal Search page content.\n- Two preserved desktop screenshots are byte-identical and the third is another near-identical desktop capture. Treat them as generic GNOME launch states only, not as evidence that a specific control has been located or changed.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Open Ubuntu Settings from the dock, app grid, or an already-open window.\n2. Reach the requested surface with the sidebar or Settings search.\n3. Find the exact row named in the task and change only that control.\n4. Keep the row visible long enough to confirm the requested toggle, mode, or selected value persists.\n5. Leave the page only after the post-change state is visible on the main Settings surface.\n\nRelevant image references, to be loaded only when their card cues match the live screenshot:\n\n- `Images/os_manage_privacy_location_proxy_and_connectivity_open_settings_surface.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_privacy_location_proxy_and_connectivity_locate_target_control.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_privacy_location_proxy_and_connectivity_apply_requested_setting.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_privacy_location_proxy_and_connectivity_verify_result_state.png`\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The Settings window is still open on the relevant page.\n- The visible row label matches the current task, not a nearby control with a similar shape.\n- The final state is persistent on the row itself: toggle position, selected option, dropdown value, checkmark, or enabled and disabled indicator.\n- If a sub-dialog or sheet was used, returning to the main Settings page still shows the requested result.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Matching one of the generic desktop cards even though the screenshot already shows a Settings page.\n- Changing a neighboring row because the label was not re-read after scrolling.\n- Reusing example values from the cards instead of the task's actual requested state.\n- Leaving Settings before the main row reflects the requested final state.",
