      "skillMarkdown": "# Manage Users Avatars and System Identity in Settings\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\nUse this skill when the task is about Ubuntu `Settings > Users`: opening the Users surface, selecting a user account, changing an identity-related control such as avatar or login behavior, creating a user, or checking a user-status result that must remain visible on the page.\n\nThis skill is a poor fit for tasks that stay outside Settings, depend on shell commands, or require copying literal example values from the screenshots. The text procedure is primary; image cards are supporting state cues.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Ubuntu Settings can be opened from the current desktop session.\n- The task names a concrete user-management outcome that can be verified from the Users page.\n- If the page is locked, be ready to use the system's unlock flow before attempting protected changes.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\n- detailed cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- Runtime cards live in `runtime_state_cards.json` and are the compact set intended for the OSWorld agent branch.\n- Load only the card whose `when_to_use` description matches the current screenshot. Do not load the whole image set by default.\n- Red boxes are interaction cues. Green boxes are verification cues. Neither one provides reusable coordinates.\n- Two images in this package are desktop-level evidence rather than clean localized Users captures, so they should be used conservatively and only when the live screen genuinely matches them.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not transfer example usernames, passwords, avatar choices, user counts, wallpaper details, desktop file names, or icon placement into a new task unless the task explicitly requires them.\n- Do not infer that a boxed region from an example screenshot exists in the same place on the live screen.\n- Treat duplicated or weak screenshots as state filters, not as proof that a target control is already found.\n\n## Procedure\n\n### 1. Reach the Users Surface\n\n- If Settings is not open, launch it from the Ubuntu desktop.\n- Navigate to `Users` from the sidebar or Settings search.\n- Keep moving until the Users page is visible; do not assume the target control is available while the screen still looks like a plain desktop.\n- Image references when relevant:\n  - `Images/os_manage_users_avatars_and_system_identity_in_settings_open_settings_surface.png`\n  - `Images/os_manage_users_avatars_and_system_identity_in_settings_locate_target_control.png`\n\n### 2. Open the Correct Account or Control\n\n- Select the relevant user entry or account details pane.\n- Identify the exact row or avatar widget named by the task.\n- Re-check the row label before acting so you do not change a neighboring control.\n- Image reference when relevant:\n  - `Images/os_manage_users_avatars_and_system_identity_in_settings_apply_requested_setting.png`\n\n### 3. Apply the Requested Change\n\n- Change only the requested user-related control.\n- If the page indicates settings are locked, unlock first and then perform the change.\n- Stay on the same page long enough to observe the control's visible new state.\n\n### 4. Verify the Result\n\n- Confirm the correct account is selected.\n- Verify the requested state from a persistent on-page cue such as a changed avatar, toggle position, status label, or user list outcome.\n- Prefer a stable text or status signal over assuming the action succeeded.\n- Image reference when relevant:\n  - `Images/os_manage_users_avatars_and_system_identity_in_settings_verify_result_state.png`\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\n- The Users sidebar entry remains selected and the page still shows the intended account.\n- The target control reflects the requested final state.\n- A stable status label such as `Logged in`, an updated avatar, or the correct visible user roster is present when that is what the task asks to verify.\n- No nearby row shows a contradictory state.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Mistaking a desktop-only screenshot for proof that the Users surface is already open.\n- Changing the wrong row because similar controls appear close together in the account detail pane.\n- Forgetting to unlock the page before trying to modify a protected setting.\n- Finishing after the click without checking that the requested state is still visible.\n\n## References\n\n- `state_cards.json` is the full detailed reference file for image-level card content.\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact runtime output for agent loading.",
