      "skillMarkdown": "# Manage Users and Groups in Terminal\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n\nUse this skill when the task is primarily a Terminal workflow involving Linux users, groups, admin membership, ownership, or permission inspection and the completion condition must be confirmed from visible shell output.\n\nTypical fits:\n- list users, groups, or the current user's identity\n- add, rename, or remove a user or group from Terminal\n- change admin or sudo membership from Terminal\n- inspect ownership or permission results with commands such as `id`, `groups`, `getent`, `ls -l`, or related shell tools\n\nDo not use this skill for GUI-only account settings unless the task explicitly returns to Terminal for the decisive verification step.\n\n## Text-First Procedure\n\n1. Open or focus Terminal and confirm you have a real shell prompt before entering commands.\n2. Run the exact user, group, ownership, or permission command required by the task.\n3. Finish only after Terminal shows explicit output proving the requested end state.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n\nThis skill stays usable without images. Use the image cards only when the live screenshot plausibly matches them.\n\n- Full detailed cards live in `state_cards.json`.\n- Compact runtime cards for the Agent branch live in `runtime_state_cards.json`.\n- Runtime should load only matching image cards, not every image in the folder.\n- Red boxes are interaction cues and green boxes are verification cues; they are never reusable coordinates.\n\nImage references used by this skill:\n- `Images/os_manage_users_and_groups_in_terminal_prepare_terminal_context.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_users_and_groups_in_terminal_run_requested_command.png`\n- `Images/os_manage_users_and_groups_in_terminal_verify_terminal_result.png`\n\nThe preserved `prepare_terminal_context` image is a nonmatching desktop capture rather than a true terminal-ready state. Keep it for audit lineage, but at runtime prefer the text rule \"look for a visible shell prompt\" and skip that image unless the current screen really matches its off-task desktop state.\n\n## Visual Transfer Limits\n\n- Do not copy literal usernames, hostnames, paths, timestamps, or permission bits from example screenshots unless the current task asks for those exact values.\n- Do not copy unrelated background apps, file-manager contents, or desktop layout from the preserved images.\n- Treat boxes as semantic hints about where to act or what to verify, not as geometry to replay.\n\n## Result Verification Cues\n\nGood terminal verification usually has all of these properties:\n- the command has finished and the prompt has returned, unless the command is intentionally interactive\n- the output explicitly names the target user, group, path, or permission state\n- no later line contradicts the claimed result with an error or different value\n\nFor account tasks, verify lines that show the final username, group list, UID/GID, or admin membership. For ownership or permission tasks, verify the final `ls -l`, `stat`, or equivalent output instead of inferring success from a silent command.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Running the right kind of command against the wrong user, group, or path.\n- Treating a typed command as completion before checking the resulting shell output.\n- Copying example literals from the screenshots instead of the task's requested values.\n- Using the preserved nonmatching desktop image as if it were a positive terminal cue.\n\n## References\n\n- Audit card set: `state_cards.json`\n- Compact runtime card set: `runtime_state_cards.json`\n- Planning source: `plan.json`",
