      "skillMarkdown": "# Apply Automatic Filters To Subfolders\n\n## Overview\n\nWork inside Thunderbird's filter workflow when a concrete rule already needs to target an account or local subfolder and stay enabled for automatic runs. Do not use this skill as the primary plan for global prefs-only tasks about whether Thunderbird can auto-apply filters to subfolders at all.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Use this skill when a concrete message filter must move or copy mail into a local or account subfolder automatically from inside the normal filter workflow.\n- Prefer this skill only after the task has clearly reached a real rule or subfolder-target workflow; for prefs-only questions about subfolder auto-apply behavior, prefer the server or advanced-prefs skill first.\n\n## Preconditions\n\n- Thunderbird is open and the current profile already contains the account or feature named in the task.\n- The requested value or destination is known before editing settings.\n\n## Atomic Capabilities\n\n- **confirm_destination_subfolder**: Create or verify the destination subfolder in the mailbox tree.\n- Derived from: Create or Rename Mail Folders\n- **bind_automatic_filter**: Set a filter action that targets the subfolder and remains enabled for automatic runs.\n- Derived from: Route Filters to Local or Account Subfolders and Enable Automatic Runs\n\n## Decision Guide\n\n- If `the destination subfolder does not exist yet`, choose `confirm_destination_subfolder`. Create or verify the subfolder first so the filter action can target a real mailbox destination.\n- If `the filter already exists, or the task explicitly asks to create or edit a concrete rule whose target is a visible subfolder`, choose `bind_automatic_filter`. Work from the Filter Rules or Message Filters dialog only when the task is genuinely about the rule itself, and verify both the subfolder target and the enabled automatic-run state there.\n\n## Visual Annotation Conventions\n\n- Red boxes mark the interactive target that should be clicked, typed into, or otherwise manipulated.\n- Green boxes mark the state signal or result change that the agent should verify before continuing.\n\n## Image References To Create\n\n- `ea9c2dd6-c7a9-44fd-8b86-efed9bbe7bbe.png`\n- `31163abf-9ec0-4297-8534-24b1a3926706.png`\n- `efc7bba1-8718-43b5-859a-5a7594cd9574.png`\n\n## Procedures\n\n### Create or confirm the destination subfolder inside the intended mailbox tree\n\n#### State-Action Mapping\n\n##### Expected Result (State 1)\n\nVisual grounding:\n- The target subfolder is visible beneath its intended parent mailbox in the Thunderbird folder tree.\n- Image reference: `Images/ea9c2dd6-c7a9-44fd-8b86-efed9bbe7bbe.png`\n\nTrigger condition:\n- The task depends on a specific mailbox subfolder destination.\n\n### Bind the filter to the subfolder and keep automatic execution enabled\n\n#### State-Action Mapping\n\n##### State 2: automatic_subfolder_rule_ready\n\nVisual grounding:\n- The Filter Rules dialog shows both the automatic-run control and the action row that targets the desired subfolder.\n- Image reference: `Images/31163abf-9ec0-4297-8534-24b1a3926706.png`\n\nTrigger condition:\n- The filter editor is already open for the target account.\n\nAction:\n- Keep automatic execution enabled and choose the requested subfolder in the move or copy action row.\n\n##### Expected Result (State 3)\n\nVisual grounding:\n- The Message Filters dialog lists the saved rule as enabled after the subfolder-targeting filter is created or edited.\n- Image reference: `Images/efc7bba1-8718-43b5-859a-5a7594cd9574.png`\n\nTrigger condition:\n- The filter editor has already been confirmed.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n\n- Saving the rule against the wrong mailbox tree because the destination subfolder was not verified first.\n- Creating the filter action correctly but leaving automatic runs disabled.\n- Opening a brand-new rule editor for a prefs-only task that really asks whether Thunderbird can auto-apply existing filters on subfolders.",
