      "skillMarkdown": "# Configure Editor Workspace and JSON Settings\n\nChange built-in VS Code settings without drifting into extensions, themes, or Python diagnostics. Use the Settings UI when visible controls exist, switch scope when the task is workspace-specific, and fall back to settings.json only when the task clearly requires direct JSON editing. The task is not complete when a search result appears; it is complete when the requested value is visibly applied in the correct scope or the saved JSON shows the requested key. Route Python-analysis settings, startup-only defaults, and background-photo workflows to their more specific sibling skills instead of keeping them inside the generic settings branch.\n\n## When This Skill Applies\n- The task changes built-in editor, workbench, or workspace behavior.\n- The task explicitly asks for settings.json editing or JSON formatting.\n\n## Visual State Card Usage\n- `runtime_state_cards.json` is the compact runtime set for agent execution.\n- `state_cards.json` is the detailed version with fuller transfer limits, bundle reasoning, and evidence lineage.\n- Red boxes mark interaction targets. Green boxes mark state or verification cues.\n- Boxes are never reusable coordinates; match by UI structure, labels, and nearby context.\n\n## Procedure\n1. Change built-in settings in the Settings UI.\n   Use this branch when A built-in setting is available as a visible UI control and the requested scope is clear.\n   Key states: `target_dropdown_visible`, `scope_selector_visible`, `numeric_setting_field_ready`, `settings_value_verified`. Verify the persistent result before stopping.\n2. Edit settings.json directly and save it.\n   Use this branch when The task explicitly calls for JSON editing or the verification checks the saved JSON key.\n   Key states: `open_settings_json_control`, `format_document_context_menu`, `settings_json_saved`. Verify the persistent result before stopping.\n\n## Common Failure Modes\n- Editing the right setting in the wrong scope.\n- Changing a visible control but never verifying the final persisted value in User versus Workspace scope.\n- Opening settings.json and forgetting to save or format the final file.\n- Editing the wrong settings scope when the task explicitly says workspace or folder settings.\n- Stopping on the settings search result without checking that the requested row, scope, and final value all match.\n- Using generic settings search for Python diagnostics, startup defaults, or workbench background workflows that have sharper sibling skills.\n\n## Transfer Limits\n- Do not copy example coordinates, filenames, workspace names, extension names, or text literals unless the live task explicitly asks for them.\n- Treat the images as state-recognition aids only. Adjust to the live VS Code labels and currently visible controls.",
